// XFAIL: *
// RUN: not %nslc -emit=mlir %s 2>&1 | %FileCheck %s
//
// M5 US4 / FR-018 — end-to-end residue fixture per US4 acceptance
// scenario 1: NSL source with `%TYPO%` reaches the IR; the
// `NSLCheckSemanticsPass` (slot 6) emits the FROZEN diagnostic.
//
// **DEFERRED at M5 — same M1 preprocessor blocker as US2 T066/T067**
// (precedent recorded in `tasks.md` T066 status note + offload
// task #23). The M1 preprocessor rejects `%TYPO%` at LEX time:
//
//   error: undefined macro reference: '%TYPO%'
//
// before the parser ever produces the AST shape that the AST→MLIR
// visitor would lower into a `nsl.reg "buf_%TYPO%"` op. So the
// residue NEVER reaches the slot-6 check; the architectural intent
// of FR-018 (residue surfaces at the M5 layer with a sourced
// diagnostic) is unreachable on PURE-NSL inputs at M5.
//
// The pass-standalone fixtures
// `test/Lower/passes/nsl-check-semantics/residue_{typo,undefined,multi}.mlir`
// exercise the slot-6 mechanics fully via hand-rolled `.mlir` —
// the substantive deliverable. End-to-end coverage waits on M1
// preprocessor amendment to either (a) admit `%IDENT%` references
// without an enclosing macro definition (forwarding the residue
// to MLIR layer per pp.ebnf §4 P3), or (b) introduce a "known-
// loop-var" allow-list that lets `%i%` etc. survive the lex.
//
// Until then this fixture is XFAIL'd. The CHECK lines preserve the
// intended diagnostic-string contract for that future amendment.

module ResidueTypo {
    reg buf_%TYPO%;
}

// CHECK: error: unresolved macro splice '%TYPO%' after structural expansion
